A Republican strategy to hinder Obama&#39;s re-election
The Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
Now, the Brennan Center considers this a myth and claims that voter fraud is less frequent in the United States than the number of people who die from lightning strikes.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: those new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what happens in Canada, the American states are responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
And along the same lines, a majority of American governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that made the registration or voting process difficult.
This phenomenon has spread since the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Consequently, during 2011, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote were introduced in 41 states.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID along with proof of US citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce the periods of early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the scrutiny and withdraw their right to vote to citizens with a criminal record.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state required voters to present photo identification.
The State of Indiana was the first to require it.
The Supreme Court of the United States in 2008 upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
Therefore, the Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to take into account that, contrary to what happens in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo identification document issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than one hundred dollars.
Thus, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people who earn less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over 65 years of age, and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have a photo ID.
And there are still more.
In many states, students, the largest voters for Democratic candidates, cannot use a photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states authorize the members of the fishing or hunting clubs that usually vote for the Republican parties to use the documents issued by said clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to file such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic party.
On the other hand, Republican legislators in 2011 supported certain laws that abolished the registration of voters on the day of the ballot in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a help desk for voters who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration drives helped register some 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 caused the new voter registration rate to fall in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have adopted laws in five other states that favor shortening the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33% of voters who voted early were African-American, while the latter represented only 13% of the voters in the state.
In the case of Hispanics, exactly the same thing happened.
These do not represent more than 11% of the voters, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, do not represent more than 46% of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vehemently opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The US Attorney&#39;s Office stepped in to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible, in part, to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of 34 states have enacted a law requiring photo identification.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted, since it is clear that they are intended to influence the results of 2012 in the key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have adopted such laws account for 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these electoral system-wide legislative changes will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: those new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
