The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused quite a stir last summer, and with good reason.
It is believed, in effect, that this boson is a participant in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what&#39;s more, it is the particle whose existence was predicted by the Standard Model: our best or &quot;least bad&quot; explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But it is not entirely clear to physicists that it is a Higgs.
We know without a doubt that a new particle exists, and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data revealed this week at a major physics conference held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data is still needed to be completely sure.
In any case, we assume that it is Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem low. We&#39;ll see what it&#39;s about.
There is, in this great world, a pervasive and inescapable law that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There&#39;s no way to break that rule, and don&#39;t try too hard, or you&#39;ll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that a law of these characteristics also exists in it: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same &quot;quantum state&quot;; a &quot;state&quot; that consists, roughly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And on the other there are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to Berkeley Laboratories&#39; The Particle Adventure website, which is extraordinary, by the way, bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we won&#39;t talk about here, and &quot;force particles&quot;, whereby large forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it should be emphasized here, are not the exotic bugs we might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or &quot;particle of light&quot; that acts as a &quot;messenger&quot; of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it &quot;disorders&quot; the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this &quot;disorder&quot; an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon; that is, one of the &quot;force-carrying&quot; bosons.
more stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be &quot;disordered&quot; for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, it is necessary to reach extremely high energies, a bit like an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide across the surface.
This is why it takes a huge particle accelerator like the one at CERN (the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 27 km in circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don&#39;t: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick to a fridge door by itself.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not.
Now, what &quot;can all this research contribute&quot;? asks Mrs. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between the observations and the predictions of the MS.
For their part, many fervently want them to meet, since the slightest difference could open a door to a &quot;new physics&quot; that covers certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, such as that it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the Universe (another oops!).
But we have not found such differences at CERN so far.
repercussions
The repercussions of such investigations on our daily lives are hard to predict, but we don&#39;t think we&#39;re wrong in saying there won&#39;t be any.
For you to see: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers in the laboratories did not suspect at all the revolution that their work would bring about.
They glimpsed the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as the physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, at first the laser was rather considered a &quot;laboratory apparatus&quot;.
Imagine...
And in addition, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the investigation.
For example, Willard Boyle himself made a light collector in 1969 in the course of his research in optics.
Despite not being his original intention at all, this sensor now serves as the &quot;eye&quot; for all the world&#39;s digital devices, earning him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
This does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but that you never know...
