Le Devoir has tried to see it up close.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in La Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was destroying him had given him a two-year respite.
&quot;They had given me five years to live, but I&#39;ve been like this for seven now,&quot; he says, made a raisin, lying on his bed at the Victor-Gadbois de Beloeil palliative care center, which he arrived the day before.
&quot;But it&#39;s always a shock, we can&#39;t be prepared for this,&quot; he continues.
The disease has wreaked havoc on him: an enormous weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone and even eating on his own.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he resignedly accepts that they help him eat.
Brave, he even manages to smile, to talk to strangers who pay him attention, bring him medicine and offer him a bath.
The bravery of ordinary death.
&quot;My greatest wish is that my diarrhea be cured, it&#39;s humiliating,&quot; he confesses.
A few hours later, the team found a remedy for that evil.
&quot;In the course of our lives we learn that a man pees standing up,&quot; says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois center.
Going back to your childhood, for certain people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
&quot;That depends on the person&#39;s ability to accept that regression,&quot; he notes.
Because, in the opinion of most people who work in palliative care, the great moments take place in the very heart of that regression.
All patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois hospice suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
In that state, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer offer &quot;curative&quot; care.
The biggest fear of Ms. A., 89, is dying &quot;conscious and drowning&quot;.
But the disease has made him discover his children.
&quot;I have some good children,&quot; he adds.
&quot;I have no more wishes left in this life,&quot; she says, before agreeing to be fitted with a mask to help her breathe.
And he expects, in the next few days, one last visit from his son who lives in Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, with a group of volunteers, body care and help with food are offered.
This is palliative care given when nothing else can be done.
To help make his death more comfortable.
In Quebec we have one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It is very little, since we know that we will all end up dying one day.
Here, life goes on in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the center&#39;s doctors.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is offered mouth rinses with brandy or Pepsi, according to the lawsuit.
Diabetics no longer have their blood sugar controlled.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served a beer to Mr. X, who died in the course of the night.
This morning, your son finished his beer at the deceased&#39;s feet.
&quot;We help both patients and their loved ones,&quot; says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
In the Victor-Gadbois center the days go by without ever being the same.
Next to a 94-year-old man enjoying his last family reunion in the courtyard, nestled between his pillows while everyone drinks to his health, a 36-year-old dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two children, having tried everything to survive.
&quot;For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by people under 45 with cancer,&quot; worries Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the Victor-Gadboisarrivent center come from home and 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient reaches the terminal phase of his life, be it at home, in hospital or in a center of care.
And several agencies, such as the Victor-Gadbois Center and the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize almost exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this relative lack of health care in Quebec that makes many doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by eminent palliative care experts such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not competent enough to ensure that everyone is entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
&quot;Recently,&quot; he recounts, &quot;I have seen a patient spend 14 days in the ER in great pain without doing what was necessary to relieve her.
I&#39;m afraid that patients want to die just because they don&#39;t get proper care.&quot;
And in parallel, many oncologists persist with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognoses.
Hélène Richard&#39;s hopes of survival were already low when she left a grueling chemotherapy treatment.
&quot;When I told my oncologist that I wanted to stop the treatment, she told me that she was very sorry that I wanted to stop fighting,&quot; he says.
&quot;However, she had told me that there was nothing else to do!&quot;
There is no almighty care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who request to die thank their caregivers for not attending to their requests once their pain has been alleviated thanks to a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful when it comes to pain management.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of home palliative care in Grand Montréal, patients do not respond to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which serves to put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can&#39;t pretend we don&#39;t understand that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved disease will have the possibility of having this palliative sedation.
The patients who are not relieved all say the same thing: &quot;I want to die.&quot;
But that does not necessarily mean &quot;I want euthanasia&quot;, but &quot;I want to be relieved.&quot;
