With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
Quite the opposite of current monetary exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing charges between parties.
Furthermore, as is often the case in technologies, the political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is at the same time a virtual currency convertible to dollars, euros, etc. and a BitTorrent-style secure exchange protocol, which allows peer-to-peer file sharing.
Nearly 200,000 transactions have been registered thanks to 15,000 computers on the network.
And about a thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a form of payment.
The bitcoin price, after having reached the top of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to 2 dollars five months later, before returning today to around ten dollars (prices are registered on the bitcoincharts page .com).
Not impressive at all when compared to world changes in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in it in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
In it, bitcoin was described as &quot;the most successful virtual currency&quot;, &quot;competing with the dollar or the euro&quot; and &quot;similar to conventional currencies&quot;.
Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as &quot;credits&quot;, used to progress in a video game and which can be earned by playing or bought (and sometimes even redeemed).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with the changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously bookkeepers, verifiers, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually made between two electronic addresses in the form of an email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are recorded in the public ledger, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction to that ledger.
This involves solving a mathematical challenge thrown at the computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file slicing, that is, transformation of a large file into a shorter and more unique digital footprint.
The computers &quot;catch&quot; the new transaction and add a number before &quot;slicing&quot; the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular fingerprint (plus leading zeros).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would be orphaned, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been hacked and escrowed bitcoins have been stolen.
&quot;The bug used does not affect the protocol itself,&quot; says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash presents the same defect.
Major players like Wikipedia reject payments of this type.
Others, like the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoin does not circulate.
In November the &quot;giant sales&quot; were launched.
&quot;$30,000 was exchanged,&quot; exults Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which turns bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of an educational book on that currency, believes a lot in the potential of this technology as well as in the transaction network.
Their system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are cheaper that way.
The bearer also manages his identity and can, therefore, remain anonymous.
The system is easy to implement in stores, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
It is enough for them to provide an address that a phone can &quot;photograph and recognize,&quot; says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement away from hierarchical systems to more horizontal systems.
“It will take a while for Bitcoin to catch on, but in 2013 there could be a turnaround,” he predicts.
On the other hand, in its report the ECB plans to reassess the various risks, today considered high, in the event that this currency is successful.
