They are drawn to the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the object of study of your research group?
- We are dedicated to human-computer interaction, but we also try to push the limits of this interaction.
For now humanity in its great mass has been trapped in the stage of working with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with a finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect as everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else does the future hold?
- Although Kinect has brought interaction to the physical level, much of it still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is still not very good.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design ones.
The world of computing must be freed to ours, to the physical, to make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space that surrounds him.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, to hell with those silly virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don&#39;t you think they overestimate it?
- Of course, it cannot be considered a panacea, the privacy issue remains to be resolved, since we do not always want others to find out about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not in loose movements, but shorter ones.
In addition, the gestures were captured not by the device&#39;s camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movement of bones and muscles.
For now it is very large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How is that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this can of soda?
You will talk and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that&#39;s going to be very hard to recognize.
- In other words, do you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at the moment?
- Not necessarily, but it is a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future we are going to have to work mainly on the design of new types of sensors that can accurately determine the reactions of the person.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, since they provide a good depth resolution, which is very important.
- If we talk about your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Are they lacking resolution, depth, or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what may be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be nice to get 8 megapixels at the speed of 1000 fps.
But the question is not in megapixels, but in the quality of the matrix and in the depth.
From this last point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives algorithm designers more work.
In other words, we have to remember not only the resolution in the X and Y axes, but also in Z.
Speed, the number of frames per second, is also important.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps is really lacking, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche from our lab in Redmond made a touch sensor with adjustable processing delay from 1 to 100 ms and it should be noted that modern mass produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
