- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh irruption in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth could well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as a support for the image.
It registers touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are truly geared towards bringing tangibility to these &quot;images in the air&quot;. For example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is located gives a sensation similar to what one feels if someone were blowing on the fingertips, but that sensation is still very weak.
There are also bracelets for the wrist that influence the nerve endings in the fingers, this too a promising direction.
- Have you tried to trick the brain?
Make him think that he feels what he seems to feel the moment he sees something?
- That&#39;s a good idea, we haven&#39;t tried it yet.
Here lies another challenge with which we will have to fight for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe that they are going to an open space, almost without end. We are also working on the idea of treadmills (not like the ones in gyms), mobile platforms, as well as giant balloons.
For now, fooling the brain is not so easy, you still have to work for many years.
That&#39;s what makes working with virtual reality attractive to researchers, that many things are in a state of complete conception.
