You can, of course, give birth in a special chamber, it will push you.
&quot;And then what?&quot; Valeri Polyakov asks himself this original question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without the sensation of gravity, the organism does not generate the skeleton or the muscular system.
It is impossible to dress a newborn in orbit in a special suit for training, like adults.
He will simply be deprived of what is vital for him.
&quot;And this experiment that we are going to do together, by allowing the birth of a child in a strange environment, will bring a disabled person to Earth, a totally maladjusted person,&quot; predicts the head of the Institute&#39;s bioethics committee. of biomedical problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Igor Pestov.
For now, the birth of children in space is a theoretical matter.
However, in time this will become a reality, when the humans in their ships head to a distant planet that will be the home for their space-born children.
NKÚ chief: The inspection of the &quot;švarc&quot; system has not found the guilty politician
When it comes to public procurement, the Czech Republic has good inspectors and quality legislation, although its enforcement limps.
This is stated by Miloslav Kala, Vice President of the Supreme Control Office (NKÚ) in an interview for Aktuálně.cz.
&quot;The law will never be perfect&quot;, but its application must be correct. &quot;This is, in my opinion, what we lack&quot;, is how he describes the current situation.
Joint checks by Czech and German inspectors also reach similar conclusions.
As an example of wrong practice, he mentions Petr Nečas&#39;s attitude towards the system of being autonomous only on paper, which is known as the &quot;švarc&quot; system.
The prime minister recently said that the ODS (Civic Democratic Party) would not bother businessmen with inspectors. So is it prohibited or allowed?
&quot;The law must be regulated in some way and if it prohibits something, in that case, not even the president of the government can prevent the action of the office that has the obligation to carry out said controls or demand obligations,&quot; says Kala.
At the meeting of the control commission in the Congress of Deputies, you spoke of the common project between the Czech and German teams, within the framework of which the legislation regarding public contracts in both countries was compared.
What exactly?
This is a parallel control that we began to carry out about two years ago.
In a simplified way: European legislation regulates how public contracts must be organized, this is followed by the legislation in force in each country and, later, the praxis itself.
We have put it all together and, although the control has not yet ended, we have obtained very interesting differences. Generally, the legislation of our country is &quot;stricter and more complete&quot;, however, the concrete praxis in some parameters is better in Germany.
It is confirmed, then, that it is not enough to incorporate increasingly strict rules, but that it is necessary to concentrate on the application of the law itself.
What can actually contribute this project? What do you think are the conclusions?
Precisely a common control of this type could help us to stop investing efforts in the concretion of the laws, the reduction and the improvement of the limits, although this does not have such a positive impact.
The thrift economy means getting the right thing at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest price) in order to avoid enrichment and, in the long run, criminal actions.
But the fact of reducing the award limit does not mean that we are going to achieve it.
Perhaps because the system is cluttered with so much &quot;paperwork&quot; that those who want to look for bugs in the system will be able to do so more easily than if the limits were kept as high as they are now.
You speak of the problems in our country with the transfer of the legislation that regulates the practice of public adjudications.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NKÚ or is it organized differently?
As for the offices, such as the NKÚ, the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors) operates there, with an organization similar to ours, with a college as well, the only thing is that in their case it is structured somewhat differently, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
Also the powers are to some extent analogous, however, as long as Germany has a federal organization, the audit courts are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Accounts (BRH) can only control federal money, what we call state funds here.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not want to make a comparison without hard data. However, Germany is still a model in some aspects, but it is not possible to specify exactly in which it is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
Surely not, but, I repeat, I don&#39;t like to make these kinds of comparisons.
It goes without saying that even those countries that we take as a model have to face a large number of problems.
If it were not so, there would be no benefit to them in collaborating with our office, would it?
Regarding the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public awards mean for your Office? Is its incidence manifested in some way?
Taking into account that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet manifested itself in the control actions.
Since we carry out ex post controls, a certain delay is necessary.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new &quot;non-economic risk detection&quot; tool, through which we have passed almost 14,000 public contracts, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and similar.
Do you consider that the approval of this law is beneficial or, rather, that it represents a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope it is.
The problem that can arise is that the regulations &quot;harden&quot; and that it is impossible to comply with them.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programs of the regional council), and each law not respected in terms of public procurement meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to toughen the law in this way?
I think not this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal mistake, which has no impact on decision making.
Such a system will only succeed in creating more bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this started path leads us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the ODS would not bother employers with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc&quot; system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and if it prohibits something, then even the prime minister of the government cannot prevent the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such controls and demand obligations.
You can say, &quot;We changed the law and allow it,&quot; but you can&#39;t say we&#39;ll just play it cool.
In the law on public adjudications, the regulations are quite strict regarding the way in which one must act formally. And this is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
