Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
It is said that in a little less than a month the end of the world will come, what do you think about it?
It is just one of many other alarmist news that we like to cling to.
The Tap Tap music group rather likes to make jokes about this and we like to say that we are the only music group in the world that manages to gather enough positive energy to postpone or avoid the end of the world.
Also, in December you organize a truly original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain it to our readers?
It&#39;s a state benefit we&#39;ve been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar set for December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The day before, December 20 at 9:00 p.m., we will organize 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at approximately the same time the Mayan calendar ends on Kiribati Island in the Pacific Ocean, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
Initially it was my idea, then we forged the project all together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and avoid the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world for our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar we have also created a unique collection of articles: boots, t-shirts, bags and original key rings against the end of the world that can be purchased at www.e-tap.cz, another way to support us.
The group The Tap Tap, along with other interpreters, also sang the so-called hymn against the end of the world, which is entitled &quot;End of the world, cancelled&quot;.
It&#39;s very popular on YouTube right now, will it be heard at benefit concerts?
Of course, and it will be the last one, well, as long as everything goes well and the world doesn&#39;t end...
All the performers will sing it at the same time in the three concerts.
The hymns will be linked to each other simultaneously thanks to the special live broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomáš Hanák has written the lyrics for this song and plays the leading role of Jesus in the video clip, where he also sings Xindl X...
How did this collaboration come about?
We even work together with other personalities from the Czech cultural scene, apart from organizing many charity events and concerts...
We put all our efforts into participating in this project.
It has been shown that most of them are interested and have fun working with us.
What will the money raised from the concerts against the end of the world be used for?
To equipment for the Studeo barrier-free educational center, which we completed in its sixth consecutive year with the civil association Tap in Jedličkův ústav.
The students of the Jedličkův ústav school are regularly visited by teachers with whom they carry out fun and interesting activities.
The students do not have sufficient financial means to pay the teachers and we make an effort to make it possible.
As part of the completion of the works in Jedličkův ústav, there will be a separate building to which we will move with this project.
Various groups and performers perform at each concert.
Which are the selection criteria?
We try to create a program that is attractive to all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform.
For more detailed information, you can consult www.kpks.cz.
Do you have any other similar &quot;spectacular action&quot; planned in the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Pražské jaro festival, so here we will surely prepare an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and personally, taking advantage of the fact that we are in the United States, I would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalist, until now you have performed, for example, in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group made up of people with disabilities.
How is the logistics and organization of these trips?
It is not as difficult as it may seem at first glance.
There are five members in an electric wheelchair, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
However, so far we have managed well. ČSA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which never ceases to amaze me.
Even in Moscow, from where we recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to the trips abroad you can compare the different attitudes of society towards the disabled and other aspects.
What have you found so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; We in Russia have witnessed that in the East there is still a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, there it is still rare for a person to move alone through the city center in an electric wheelchair.
Something as common as, for example, giving preference to someone in a wheelchair in an elevator, it is not there.
Luckily, a civil association has been created that makes an effort to make the problems of people with disabilities thematic.
In what aspects should we take the example of more advanced countries?
There are many aspects in which we are behind...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the people it directly affects.
In London and Madrid it is very normal for people with a severe disability to move on their own in public and to go to the toilet, to the museum, wherever they want...
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to participate actively in social life, in this regard, with The Tap Tap, we are a little ahead!
A respectful or barrier-free society is one thing, but when the time comes when eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers emerge, it will really start to change everything.
Until now, they are isolated cases of people who have great willpower.
The group The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we look back a few years, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I entered Jedličkův ústav as an educator, where I had a lot of young people around me who wanted to dedicate themselves to something.
And since I am a musician, I play the saxophone among others, I founded an amateur group with a co-worker.
And over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, it got a little out of hand (laughs).
However, popularity did not come until recent years, or am I wrong?
It is true that connecting with famous singers and also actively working to promote the group helped us a lot.
We came to the conclusion that the work that is not seen is as if it did not exist.
Thanks to aid from the European Union, we can also afford quality teachers, equipment, etc.
Did you intend to go that far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I saw the potential that there was, that something can be done in a different way.
Show business is full of things that look alike.
It is logical, in its own way, everything new is welcomed with caution and takes a long time to be accepted.
There are few extraordinary things, but I dare say The Tap Tap is one of them.
The impression of someone who sees us for the first time is clearly compassion, it is a natural reaction...
But compassion is totally superfluous because people with disabilities are not abandoned suffering beings that we should have compassion on.
There are people who are capable of living a full life and developing themselves, provided, of course, that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something goes well for people with disabilities, then it is not only progress for them, but for the whole of society.
Did the fact that you are a demanding boss, as many people describe you, help?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be rigorous in many aspects and demand a certain discipline.
I think it&#39;s completely normal.
Some people arrive with a romantic vision and their heads in the clouds and when they find out that they have to attend two days of rehearsals, go to the preparatory test and spend a lot of time traveling and in concerts, the initial euphoria quickly leaves them.
But that&#39;s how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and achieve something.
Currently the group The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were already there at the beginning of 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group, people come and go, it can&#39;t be helped.
Whoever has the will and desire will always find the doors open
