Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency countries held last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second ESA member country from the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on November 12, 2008).
Poland began an intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the agency&#39;s project committee.
However, Poland&#39;s path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in spaceflight before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. Šternfeld&#39;s lecture at the Warsaw astronomical observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study &quot;Introduction to Cosmonautics&quot;.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize in France for his &quot;Introduction to Cosmonautics&quot;.
Doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, he was known throughout the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
Already in the year 1925 a train was built in Poland that was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who the author of the proposal was and the details of the project are not known either.
It is not clear if the rocket was going to be used to start the car or to stop it.
Information about this carriage is limited to what was reported in the press of the time.
From the year 1933 the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was funded by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the investigation reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937, the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by the engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study &quot;Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza&quot; by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was in charge of all projects on missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The society was first referenced in the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine with four very long articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, from prof. M. Subotowicze, proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, projects for artificial satellites had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to become part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA was significantly involved in the development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) sounding rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket on which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the construction of the RM-1A version was finished and in the summer of 1959 air tests of the RM-2 two-stage rockets began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was to be the subject of actual scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was going to have an apogee of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, in 1962 the works were suspended.
The successor to the first rockets of the RM type was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and a starting weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (named Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, differing from each other in the space available for scientific apparatus.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum apogee in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg up to 60 km in altitude.
Subsequently the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version was built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the cosmic space investigation on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remek.
The suspension of the law on social work is not the solution.
Last week the constitutional court suspended the social work law.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
Of course it will be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of more economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with rampant financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labor cost (wages) produces economic stress.
Under this concept, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, by importing cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and to do so &quot;causes a drop&quot; in the competitor&#39;s price with the aim of taking over the majority of the market and, Thus, you increase your profit margin.
On a large scale means, for most entrepreneurs, moving production abroad, buying cheaper there, or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labor, compared to other economies, is higher.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and, therefore, is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the state&#39;s social spending necessarily grows.
This whole situation favors the total disinterest of businessmen in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damage that they have caused in their eagerness to obtain benefits.
The situation is universally so well known that it is not necessary to present specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of these countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially lowering the social level of their own population and, in this way, attracting foreign capital to the market. country.
Put another way, governments make private capital available to their own population without regard to social decline.
This becomes evident especially in the changes of the current laws.
The goal is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the economic obligation system in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the restricted right of employees in terms of labor rights.
The result is growing poverty along with widening gaps between rich and poor.
For a number of years there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot support themselves with their own work.
The number of people who receive this type of help already reaches one million.
Within the framework of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, a quite frequent case occurs: people employed with such a low salary that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
One such scandal related to the situation of auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
The saving measures of practically all the southern states of the EU lead, without a doubt, to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to live poorly with a lousy salary on the edge of society, hoping that one day private investment capital will arrive in the country.
Is it necessary to wonder where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never arrives, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny part of a European salary.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media say ad nauseam that the state should not provide capital to the economy, that running the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends tooth and nail the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by meddling with control.
Next, it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence the political march with its selfishness and, therefore, the entire state.
In this case the answer is clearly affirmative.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, in mutual favors, in a legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but is not punishable.
In Germany the situation is as follows: State ministries, lacking financial means, entrust the drafting of bills to private legal firms, which are often linked to industry.
These types of bills are then approved in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
