Szabo: &quot;The Germans must play a more leading role&quot;
Germany has abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, this puts Berlin in a tricky diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier in the week, Germany hinted that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories United Nations observer state status.
Ultimately, however, Berlin abstained.
Because?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the country&#39;s special relationship with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time, I don&#39;t think it supports the US position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising that took place in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position when important international issues are at stake?
Yes that&#39;s how it is.
This is because it is currently reorienting its foreign policy away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and towards a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that the Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans find themselves at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to doing so.
I think they are still feeling their role, but they are already on the path to a &quot;normal&quot; foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to that of countries like France or Great Britain.
What exactly does a &quot;normal&quot; foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds a strong motivation in economic policy, that is, in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers and for this reason Germany must protect their interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken regarding the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason, it must be careful not to alienate itself from Arab public opinion or even from Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not give it so much importance since it is not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a pivotal role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the US by abstaining from voting on major decisions like the Palestine vote?
I think that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I don&#39;t think there has been as sharp a breakout as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps with this Germany has managed to earn a certain respect.
After all, all this has only shown that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe there are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the US has come out clearly in favor of a veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of US domestic politics.
I think the Obama administration secretly shows great understanding of the European position.
But, because of the political situation that exists here, it is evident that the government cannot defend this position in public.
I believe that the true disparity of opinions does not really have the magnitude that is attributed to it.
If we analyze the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he is developing.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that is precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
Therefore, they do not have the possibility of being part of a superior entity, but must drive things from their own position.
That is precisely what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in forcing Europe to adopt a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, whether simply because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a tricky subject.
But I think the Germans are clear that they have to play the role of an independent figure.
Does Germany see itself in the role of a major international player? Does Germany really want to take a leading role?
Or perhaps you still find it difficult to accept that leadership?
Germany still hasn&#39;t gotten used to it, it&#39;s always a bit awkward and, for obvious reasons, the country still struggles to play a bigger role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany positions itself as the main player, certain anti-German sentiments are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
It is an old problem and it is that nobody wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
Seen in this light, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
You have to be receptive to different neighbors and opinions, and that&#39;s not easy.
The influence of the US in European politics is diminishing more and more, but the EU does not fill that gap at the moment, who is left then?
The Germans will have no choice but to assume a more leading role.
Even if they don&#39;t like it, if they find it unpleasant or if it makes them an even more unpopular people, c&#39;est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly discuss the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
&quot;Brand protection&quot; in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a globally known brand and Polo Ralph Lauren too.
But what is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is a name officially registered in China that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it is protected as long as the true eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it is not clear that they will be proved right.
&quot;Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,&quot; says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at the Taylor Wessing law firm specializing in copyright violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case arrives at my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters in order to register their trademarks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and Prada-Kny is registered instead of Prada.
German companies also copy legally in the same way, as has happened to the sporting goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet in which he keeps entries from the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the Zegna DF Puma brand, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are department stores with several floors dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, the Pattloch cases are of a different nature. On behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to profit from a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it &quot;Bang Ming Pai&quot; or companion mark.
The word originates from the Chinese term &quot;Bang Dakuan&quot;,
which refers to women who have &quot;fished&quot; a rich man.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty
&quot;It&#39;s bad for business, you have to fight it,&quot; Pattloch demands.
&quot;The brand is leaking, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage suffered by the image is enormous.&quot;
The financial losses and legal costs of the affected sectors are in the millions, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15,000 million euros per year, China is the third largest market for luxury goods and the fastest growing.
However, achieving the annulment of registrations of dubious legality in the trademark registry is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
The processes can last up to nine years and the result is uncertain.
Pattloch talks about cases where the court dismissed a lawsuit because so much time had elapsed that the name in the lawsuit had already become a &quot;market reality.&quot;
&quot;If the plaintiff is unlucky, they may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged the plagiarist&#39;s brand in China,&quot; Pattloch says.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against the construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been taken over by the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That is why today the Chinese can continue to use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo buyer Geely initially used a blue and white logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter went to court and Geely had to amend it.
Clothing maker Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo depicted a crocodile facing the opposite direction from the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing acknowledges that in 2010 they had difficulties due to a shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, &quot;the labor emergency situation returned to normal.&quot;
In this way, the number of unprocessed claim processes has been reduced by 22%.
Almost 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims are still pending resolution.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As usual in China, the numbers are staggering.
Last year the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million applications for trademark protection, almost a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means that China leads the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, according to the trademark office.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, a figure that amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, they would have pocketed 1.8 billion yuan in rights.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese impersonator.
Although the Germans have succeeded in stopping the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the copycat has managed to secure the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
&quot;We ourselves have caused this situation because surnames are not protected in Germany,&quot; says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialties in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the Munich appeal.
In the next two instances they have agreed with Freudenberg, but the opposing party is still fighting today.
You have to be very careful
Now the case has reached the doors of the Superior Court of Justice, where it is still pending resolution.
Wentzler is confident that he can resolve the issue favorably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that &quot;the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time.&quot;
Internal costs are difficult to estimate; The business archive has had to review files that are up to a hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposing party a &quot;six-figure sum in euros&quot; with the aim of reaching an amicable agreement, but was unsuccessful.
&quot;This shows how much we care,&quot; Wentzler says.
The dangers lurking in the Far East even threaten Europe,
specifically if imitators secure the rights to unprotected trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register the Freudenberg name for shoes and leather goods in Germany.
The group has long since abandoned this commercial field, however it managed to prevent registration.
&quot;You have to be extremely careful,&quot; Wentzler says.
Both he and attorney Pattloch advise German companies to be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international legislation on trademark rights, but what must be done is &quot;also register in China everything that may be susceptible to protection&quot;, as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the theme can turn out to be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, if Freudenberg lost the last round of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party license fees for his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or in the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
World AIDS Day: dance, sing, help
In Heidelberg the Imbongi choir rehearses and in Swaziland AIDS orphans rejoice
The story of a bond capable of overcoming much more than 8,733 kilometers of distance.
First you start with the dance: cowboy boots, basketball shoes, high heels and loafers search for the beat on the parquet floor, and find it quickly.
One, two, three, four.
Only then do the singers&#39; voices (alto, bass, tenor and soprano) begin to rise slowly, swirling, dulling and following each other.
And Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old director, threatens to go off the deep end trying to bring order with his soft, energetic gestures.
It&#39;s Monday afternoon and in the music room of the Heidelberg Institute for Medical Psychology the Imbongi Choir is rehearsing a new song.
The fifty singers have also arrived, between the ages of 23 and 69, from the human geneticist to the householder.
&quot;Om&#39;Obani&quot; is not an easy piece, each voice in the choir has a different text and also in a barely known foreign language: Zulu, a language spoken by eleven million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and in some areas of Swaziland.
Help for self-help
According to an estimate by UNAIDS, the United Nations program to fight AIDS, around the world there are approximately 34 million people infected with the HIV virus.
23.5 million of them live in southern Africa.
In Swaziland there are 245,000 AIDS orphans.
More than 40% of the population is already HIV positive.
The Voices for Africa association has found sponsors in Germany for the 180 AIDS orphans from the village of Esitjeni.
Seventy of them attend secondary school.
For 15 or 20 euros a month you can sponsor a child.
This contribution will cover school tuition, uniform and will guarantee you one hot meal a day at the Gogo Center.
Imbongi means &quot;storyteller&quot; or &quot;panegyrist&quot; in Zulu.
In this room no one knows how to speak this Bantu language fluently, but they do know how to sing.
For ten years this choir has been rehearsing songs in this soft foreign language that sometimes manages to transport them to their place of origin: southern Africa.
8,733 kilometers as the crow flies from Heidelberg, in the northeast of the kingdom of Swaziland, there is a town called Esitjeni that depends on the voices of this German choir.
Forty percent are infected
Approximately 2,000 people live there, some still in simple mud and straw huts, a large part of them children.
More than 300 no longer have parents because they have succumbed to AIDS.
Esitjeni is a small example of what ails Swaziland: the highest AIDS infection rate and the lowest life expectancy in the world, according to UNICEF.
The population does not look favorably on circumcision, a practice that has been shown to halve the risk of contagion.
More than 40% of the inhabitants of Swaziland are carriers of the immunodeficiency virus, and dying in their thirties has become commonplace.
During a joint trip to Africa in the spring of 2005, the choir discovered this remote town, but what they saw above all were many children on the streets who lacked not only the protection of their parents, but the main thing: food, clothing and training.
Without a school degree, the chances in a poor country are more than slim.
In the beginning, it was only the private commitment of a few that made it possible for a child to go to school and enjoy a hot meal a day. All this for a few euros.
However, a year later the choir founded the association &quot;Voices for Africa&quot; which has since professionally cared for AIDS orphans in Esitjeni.
Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STDs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common STDs of viral origin are AIDS, the human papilloma virus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Crabs and scabies are among the STDs transmitted by parasites.
What are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur more often in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five syphilis cases reported in Germany originate from sexual contact between men.
In the case of heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomonas, human papillomavirus, candidiasis (fungus) and gonorrhea.
HIV transmission among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively low; however, approximately 20% of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In our country, the human papilloma virus is also added to the most common diseases among youth.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been on a downward trend since 2007.
In 2011, approximately 2,700 cases were registered.
This is one tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate that it is a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort when urinating, flow, abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
Often they do not cause pain or cause other symptoms and therefore go undetected.
How can one protect oneself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of contagion, but they do not offer 100% protection.
Some sexually transmitted disease pathogens can also be transmitted through infections from dirt and physical contact.
For this reason, experts recommend regular medical examinations, especially if you frequently change sexual partners.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any late consequences can be avoided.
Through collaborations, donations and, last but not least, the fees the choir charges for their performances throughout Germany, they manage to raise quite a bit of money.
