The hardest job in the world: Kawah Ijen&#39;s human mules
For four euros, the porters of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to go down every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas that emanates from the bowels of the Earth solidifies when it comes into contact with the air.
After uprooting large sulfur boulders, which together weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two bamboo baskets that he carries on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters, but it takes more than 40 minutes for the exhausted porters to ascend at a snail&#39;s pace, keeping their balance and carefully timing their steps so as not to slip and fall off the ground. the precipice.
They know that any misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract
Once at the top, they make their way through the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, laboriously carrying the heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little below, at 1,850 meters above sea level.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupiahs (5 euro cents) for each kilo of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry, since this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
&quot;Since the normal thing is to carry 70 kilos, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,&quot; explains Anto, who usually makes three daily shipments.
It takes three hours for each one and he ends up exhausted, but they allow him to collect 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems like a pittance for such an inhuman effort, it is triple what he would earn on the field.
&quot;The miners&#39; wages are very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),&quot; the porter clarifies. who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the cut was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a compelling reason that, in Indonesia, is as blunt as brimstone: &quot;I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I have brought her to Java to convert to Islam.&quot;
Anto has asthma, he is breathing hard, coughing constantly, and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases
At 27, Anto has been risking his skin at Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll on him despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, is breathing hard, coughs constantly, and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases emitted by the volcano.
It is the price you must pay to achieve your dream.
&quot;I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,&quot; he promises in more than passable English.
Grounded by life, this likeable and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he works as a mule.
Sharing a filthy wooden cabin with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the dark.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends into the crater lighting up with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
Some 400 porters carry the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its huge profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs, nor does it supply any equipment to the porters, who work on their own and both by weight.
In fact, they don&#39;t even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera that, together with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the rangers of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
&quot;This job is for beasts and not for people,&quot; protests Madrusin, a stocky 42-year-old porter who has been on the Kawah Ijen for three decades, since he left school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will endure working &quot;as long as he can&quot; because he needs the money to educate his three children, between the ages of 18 and 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so tough that no one complains of serious illness... beyond, of course, of his usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pain in his knees and sores on his shoulders, which have become malformed by the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at 53 years old.
Every day, he and his colleagues extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away, along a goat track through the undergrowth.
&quot;I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life,&quot; Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth wide, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30, also works loading sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest trades in the world: the one performed by the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
Singapore seeks babies to save economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress and the cost of property and education for not having children.
&quot;Singapore&#39;s population needs to grow.&quot;
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, let&#39;s do our civic duty and create life!
It may seem implausible that these verses are part of an ad for mints, but despite - or perhaps because of - the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lines are part of a rap that uses local references like &quot;Let&#39;s put a bao (bun) in the oven&quot; to make fun of Singapore&#39;s birthrate.
The ad company that made the video, BBH, is hoping that the ad will bring attention to the problem in a fun way.
