This is pure internet stuff so we had to make it fun and funny.
It is the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world at reproducing ourselves so we felt this was an issue we needed to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things, like launching pheromone perfumes or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn&#39;t necessarily work.
So we thought, why don&#39;t we get as creative as possible to solve this problem, which is writing a rap?
1.2 children
The one that does not take it so lightly is the Singapore government.
He spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and doles out tax breaks.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
Singapore&#39;s birth rate, according to its national population division, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 - known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why aren&#39;t Singaporeans having more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Division, says it&#39;s because of &quot;better education&quot; and &quot;a wider range of career opportunities.&quot;
&quot;That has given people a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond getting married and starting a family,&quot; he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in singleness, and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decline in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy that aims to drastically increase immigration to cope with population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore there are websites where thinly disguised xenophobia abounds against many new immigrants, particularly Chinese, whom they criticize for keeping wages low and not integrating.
Rising immigration is also seen as one of the reasons Singapore&#39;s ruling party experienced its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with higher fees and levies for foreign workers.
unexpected consequences
While falling birth rates have known effects on a nation&#39;s economic growth, tax revenues, healthcare costs, and immigration policies, the Singapore example is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government tries not to build so many small houses.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has come to control the number of small apartments, known as &quot;shoeboxes&quot;, that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have surfaces of 46 square meters and have been very successful sellers.
However, there is concern that they may promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers from building large, family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate company EL Developers, says his &quot;shoeboxes&quot; sell much faster than the larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that units sell out days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new rules provide clearer guidance for developers, who previously were hampered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
too stressed
Singapore is a city state.
While these new rules may be a step toward increasing the national birth rate, speaking to Singaporeans who work in the central business district, it sounds like they won&#39;t have much of an effect.
&quot;People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so many people are putting it off,&quot; says a young executive.
Other people may have children.
&quot;But for me it&#39;s important to have my own money and time,&quot; says another young man in his 20s.
Men and women mention their career, stress and the cost of property and education as the reasons that prevent them from having children.
So as much as the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans call the shots.
