Unasur Summit ends without making public the Lima Declaration
The VI Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven attending leaders.
Efe repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources from the Foreign Ministry and the Presidency indicated at first that they were going to deliver it after the closure, but later they affirmed that in At some point it will be published on the Peruvian Government website.
When consulted about the text, they indicated that the content had been exposed by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists&#39; access to Summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the silent video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room with the message &quot;private session, restricted audio.&quot;
The little information that circulated among the reporters was delivered by the press spokespersons of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian one.
The only document released during the day was the list of attending presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the Presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the &quot;final declaration&quot; of the summit, but it is Humala&#39;s pronouncement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the III Summit of South America-Arab Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was not disseminated either.
On the official ASPA website it can be confirmed that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities made an effort to have secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the obtaining of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling from the Court in The Hague to settle a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (ICJ), which begins on Monday in The Hague to hear the arguments of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
&quot;We will abide by and execute the ruling that defines the differences that we are taking to this international court today,&quot; Humala said, along with his Chilean counterpart.
&quot;Chile has been, is, and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties, and international tribunals,&quot; Piñera added, shaking hands with Humala, along with to the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ occurred after Colombia denounced this week the Pact of Bogotá by which it had accepted to submit to the rulings of that international court, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered seriously erroneous. .
The summit was held with the absences of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he informed that 16 agreements were adopted and lines of action were established for 31 projects between South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take &quot;important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are expanding the agreements on residence.&quot;
He reported that actions are being promoted to improve &quot;cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and against transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, low-priced internet access in all corners of South America, and provide jointly and efficiently the risks of natural disasters&quot;.
With a Europe in crisis, &quot;the economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphal matrix, but should serve to expand our productive matrix and envision a better future for our peoples,&quot; added Humala.
&quot;We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of spaces in South America, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,&quot; said the Peruvian president in a message read.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
Likewise, the final document mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
&quot;We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for his reincorporation into the Union of South American Nations,&quot; from which he is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and of good relations between neighbors, was another of the issues highlighted by the summit.
In this sense, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before beginning his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to respectfully discuss the maritime dispute after a ruling of the ICJ, questioned by Bogotá.
